{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
'''Out of Wallet''' refers to private data used for [[authentication]] in activities such as [[telephone banking]] or [[internet banking]] to prevent [[identity theft]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Out Of Wallet {{!}} Credit Bureau Connection|url = https://www.creditbureauconnection.com/compliance_solutions/index.php?category=compliance_solutions&content=out_of_wallet|website = www.creditbureauconnection.com|accessdate = 2015-07-06}}</ref> The practice may part of a [[knowledge-based authentication]] process.
Ideally, out of wallet information is easily recallable by a user but obscure to most other persons and difficult for them to uncover. Prompts for out of wallet questions are now often generated automatically through convergence of [[database]]s containing users' financial transactions, vehicle registrations, and other records.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = Certain ID - ID Analytics|url = http://www.idanalytics.com/solutions/authentication-and-verification/certain-id/|accessdate = 2015-07-06}}</ref>
Typical out of wallet questions a user may be asked include:
#What was the color of your first car? #What is the name of the first school you attended? #What is the name of the hospital you were born in?
Such information is available to a database compiler but may not be readily available to [[criminal]]s attempting to commit identity theft.<ref name=":0" />
